stories: Recently, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) have been proposed as a novel generalization to classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) by utilizing quantum mechanisms. These quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient training process in QCNNs by reducing the input size from $n$ to $log_2n$. This paper implements and compares both CNNs and QCNNs by testing losses and prediction accuracy on three commonly used datasets: MNIST hand-written digits, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog face images. Additionally, data augmentation (DA), a technique commonly used in CNNs to improve classification performance by generating similar images based on original inputs, is also implemented in QCNNs. Surprisingly, the results showed that DA did not improve QCNNs performance. The reasons and logic behind this result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantum machine learning theory.

Quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) have recently been proposed as a novel generalization of classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs), utilizing quantum mechanisms to reduce the input size from $n$ to $log_2n$. This paper implements and compares both CNNs and QCNNs on three commonly used datasets: MNIST hand-written digits, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog face images. The results show that data augmentation (DA) does not improve QCNNs performance, and the reasons and logic behind this result are discussed.

In this paper, we implement and compare quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) with classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) on three common datasets: MNIST, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog face images.
